{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **1. Concept Overview: Polynomial Regression**\n","\n","When the relationship between explanatory and response variables violates the assumption of linearity, one solution is to use a polynomial regression model. This is done by adding polynomial terms to the model:\n","\n","$$y = w_1x + w_2x^2 + \\dots + w_dx^d + b$$\n","\n","Where $d$ denotes the degree of the polynomial. Even though it is used to model non-linear relationships, it is technically still considered a **multiple linear regression model** because the regression coefficients ($w$) remain linear."],"metadata":{"id":"eZT9RZeyJ9hq"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **2. Toy Problem: Adding Polynomial Terms with scikit-learn**\n","\n","The `PolynomialFeatures` transformer class from scikit-learn is used to add polynomial terms to a dataset. The following code demonstrates how to fit a simple linear regression model alongside a quadratic (degree=2) model to a toy dataset, plot the results, and compare their Mean Squared Error (MSE) and $R^2$ scores."],"metadata":{"id":"N2F7RDb3KDhL"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import numpy as np\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures\n","from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n","from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score\n","\n","# 1. Prepare data and add a second-degree polynomial term\n","X = np.array([258.0, 270.0, 294.0, 320.0, 342.0,\n","              368.0, 396.0, 446.0, 480.0, 586.0])[:, np.newaxis]\n","y = np.array([236.4, 234.4, 252.8, 298.6, 314.2,\n","              342.2, 360.8, 368.0, 391.2, 390.8])\n","\n","lr = LinearRegression()\n","pr = LinearRegression()\n","quadratic = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)\n","X_quad = quadratic.fit_transform(X)\n","\n","# 2. Fit a simple linear regression model for comparison\n","lr.fit(X, y)\n","X_fit = np.arange(250, 600, 10)[:, np.newaxis]\n","y_lin_fit = lr.predict(X_fit)\n","\n","# 3. Fit a multiple regression model on the transformed features\n","pr.fit(X_quad, y)\n","y_quad_fit = pr.predict(quadratic.fit_transform(X_fit))\n","\n","# 4. Plot the results\n","plt.scatter(X, y, label='Training points')\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_lin_fit, label='Linear fit', linestyle='--')\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_quad_fit, label='Quadratic fit')\n","plt.xlabel('Explanatory variable')\n","plt.ylabel('Predicted or known target values')\n","plt.legend(loc='upper left')\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()\n","\n","# 5. Compute MSE and R^2 evaluation metrics\n","y_lin_pred = lr.predict(X)\n","y_quad_pred = pr.predict(X_quad)\n","\n","mse_lin = mean_squared_error(y, y_lin_pred)\n","mse_quad = mean_squared_error(y, y_quad_pred)\n","print(f'Training MSE linear: {mse_lin:.3f}, quadratic: {mse_quad:.3f}')\n","\n","r2_lin = r2_score(y, y_lin_pred)\n","r2_quad = r2_score(y, y_quad_pred)\n","print(f'Training R^2 linear: {r2_lin:.3f}, quadratic: {r2_quad:.3f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Training MSE linear: 569.780, quadratic: 61.330\n","Training R^2 linear: 0.832, quadratic: 0.982\n"]}],"execution_count":11,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":522},"id":"iuQL-8xnJ9ht","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781877783732,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":466,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"4a7b5fe1-ed2c-4079-cab7-d6224489356b"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **3. Application: Ames Housing Dataset**\n","\n","Applying these concepts to real-world data (the Ames Housing dataset), we can compare linear, quadratic, and cubic models.\n","\n","* **Living Area:** For the relationship between living area and sale price, polynomial features do not add much value because the underlying relationship is largely linear.\n","* **Overall Quality:** For the relationship between overall house quality and sale price, quadratic and cubic fits capture the non-linear relationship much better than a simple linear fit.\n","\n","*(Note: The following code assumes you have already loaded the Ames Housing dataset into a pandas DataFrame named `df`.)*"],"metadata":{"id":"Geao5tuyJ9hu"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import pandas as pd\n","\n","# Define the subset of columns to use\n","columns = ['Gr Liv Area', 'Overall Qual', 'SalePrice']\n","\n","# Load the dataset\n","df = pd.read_csv('http://jse.amstat.org/v19n3/decock/AmesHousing.txt',\n","                 sep='\\t',\n","                 usecols=columns)\n","\n","# Drop rows containing missing values (Total Bsmt SF has 1 missing value)\n","df = df.dropna(axis=0)"],"metadata":{"id":"eOrgn6AVKdVL","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781877783739,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":3,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}}},"execution_count":12,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **4. Modeling Living Area vs. Sale Price**"],"metadata":{"id":"JM5nAB8aLrz5"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Strip outliers that might skew the regression fits\n","X = df[['Gr Liv Area']].values\n","y = df['SalePrice'].values\n","X = X[(df['Gr Liv Area'] < 4000)]\n","y = y[(df['Gr Liv Area'] < 4000)]\n","\n","regr = LinearRegression()\n","\n","# Create quadratic and cubic features\n","quadratic = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)\n","cubic = PolynomialFeatures(degree=3)\n","X_quad = quadratic.fit_transform(X)\n","X_cubic = cubic.fit_transform(X)\n","\n","# Fit models to features\n","X_fit = np.arange(X.min()-1, X.max()+2, 1)[:, np.newaxis]\n","\n","regr = regr.fit(X, y)\n","y_lin_fit = regr.predict(X_fit)\n","linear_r2 = r2_score(y, regr.predict(X))\n","\n","regr = regr.fit(X_quad, y)\n","y_quad_fit = regr.predict(quadratic.fit_transform(X_fit))\n","quadratic_r2 = r2_score(y, regr.predict(X_quad))\n","\n","regr = regr.fit(X_cubic, y)\n","y_cubic_fit = regr.predict(cubic.fit_transform(X_fit))\n","cubic_r2 = r2_score(y, regr.predict(X_cubic))\n","\n","# Plot results\n","plt.scatter(X, y, label='Training points', color='lightgray')\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_lin_fit, label=f'Linear (d=1), $R^2$={linear_r2:.2f}',\n","         color='blue', lw=2, linestyle=':')\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_quad_fit, label=f'Quadratic (d=2), $R^2$={quadratic_r2:.2f}',\n","         color='red', lw=2, linestyle='-')\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_cubic_fit, label=f'Cubic (d=3), $R^2$={cubic_r2:.2f}',\n","         color='green', lw=2, linestyle='--')\n","\n","plt.xlabel('Living area above ground in square feet')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price in U.S. dollars')\n","plt.legend(loc='upper left')\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":13,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"a31xt6oOJ9hv","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781877783943,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":202,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"4287610f-596b-463f-e35d-412c23367a76"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **5. Modeling Overall Quality vs. Sale Price**"],"metadata":{"id":"LfiD2S9KL_Oj"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# 1. Extract the Overall Qual and SalePrice features\n","X = df[['Overall Qual']].values\n","y = df['SalePrice'].values\n","\n","regr = LinearRegression()\n","\n","# 2. Create quadratic and cubic features\n","quadratic = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)\n","cubic = PolynomialFeatures(degree=3)\n","X_quad = quadratic.fit_transform(X)\n","X_cubic = cubic.fit_transform(X)\n","\n","# 3. Fit models to features\n","# The quality scale is 1-10, so an X_fit range from 0 to 11 provides a clean curve\n","X_fit = np.arange(0, 12, 1)[:, np.newaxis]\n","\n","# Linear Fit\n","regr = regr.fit(X, y)\n","y_lin_fit = regr.predict(X_fit)\n","linear_r2 = r2_score(y, regr.predict(X))\n","\n","# Quadratic Fit\n","regr = regr.fit(X_quad, y)\n","y_quad_fit = regr.predict(quadratic.fit_transform(X_fit))\n","quadratic_r2 = r2_score(y, regr.predict(X_quad))\n","\n","# Cubic Fit\n","regr = regr.fit(X_cubic, y)\n","y_cubic_fit = regr.predict(cubic.fit_transform(X_fit))\n","cubic_r2 = r2_score(y, regr.predict(X_cubic))\n","\n","# 4. Plot the results\n","plt.scatter(X, y, label='Training points', color='lightgray')\n","\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_lin_fit,\n","         label=f'Linear (d=1), $R^2$={linear_r2:.2f}',\n","         color='blue', lw=2, linestyle=':')\n","\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_quad_fit,\n","         label=f'Quadratic (d=2), $R^2$={quadratic_r2:.2f}',\n","         color='red', lw=2, linestyle='-')\n","\n","plt.plot(X_fit, y_cubic_fit,\n","         label=f'Cubic (d=3), $R^2$={cubic_r2:.2f}',\n","         color='green', lw=2, linestyle='--')\n","\n","plt.xlabel('Overall quality of the house')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price in U.S. dollars')\n","plt.legend(loc='upper left')\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":487},"id":"__N1XFRRLhUk","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781877784148,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":204,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"25785cfb-5233-4c4e-989a-e57bf1cb6b65"},"execution_count":14,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Important Caveat: Overfitting**\n","\n","While adding polynomial terms can help capture complex relationships, increasing the complexity of your model by adding more and more polynomial features also increases the likelihood of **overfitting**. In practice, always evaluate your model's performance on a separate, unseen test dataset to properly estimate how well it generalizes."],"metadata":{"id":"nw4cRYVWJ9hv"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}